      <div class="arch-title-col">
        <h3 class="arch-title">Curated Memory</h3>
        <a href="#" class="arch-link">View Spec &#8594;</a>
      </div>
      <div class="arch-desc-col">
        <p class="arch-desc">Not a vector dump. Signet's memory system uses hybrid retrieval (semantic + keyword), importance decay, and a four-tier taxonomy (session, episodic, semantic, procedural) to surface what matters <em>right now</em> -- not everything that was ever stored. Your agent learns what to forget.</p>
        <p class="arch-scenario">Switch from Cursor to Claude Code mid-project? Your agent remembers your architectural decisions, patterns, deploy setup -- and doesn't waste context on last month's debugging notes.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="arch-item">
      <div class="arch-icon">
        <svg width="32" height="32" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><rect x="3" y="11" width="18" height="10"/><path d="M7 11V7a5 5 0 0 1 10 0v4"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="arch-title-col">
        <h3 class="arch-title">Secrets &amp; Injection Safety</h3>
        <a href="#" class="arch-link">Learn More &#8594;</a>
      </div>
      <div class="arch-desc-col">
        <p class="arch-desc">API keys encrypted at rest with libsodium. Secret values are never returned in model output -- even if a prompt injection attack tries to extract them. Agents use credentials through a secure proxy that redacts values from all output streams. The only agent framework with built-in prompt injection protection for secrets.</p>
        <p class="arch-scenario">Your agent needs OPENAI_API_KEY to run evals and CLOUDFLARE_TOKEN to deploy. A malicious prompt tries to extract them. Signet's output redaction catches it before it leaves the sandbox.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="arch-item">
      <div class="arch-icon">
        <svg width="32" height="32" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><rect x="3" y="3" width="7" height="7" rx="1"/><rect x="14" y="3" width="7" height="7" rx="1"/><rect x="3" y="14" width="7" height="7" rx="1"/><path d="M14 17.5h7M17.5 14v7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="arch-title-col">
        <h3 class="arch-title">Skills Registry</h3>
        <a href="#" class="arch-link">Browse Skills &#8594;</a>
      </div>
      <div class="arch-desc-col">
        <p class="arch-desc">Install, vet, and manage agent skills from a curated registry. Skills are sandboxed -- they can access the capabilities they declare but nothing else. Review skill permissions before installation. No supply-chain surprises.</p>
        <p class="arch-scenario">Your agent needs browser automation. <code>signet skill install browser-use</code> -- review its declared permissions, approve, done. The skill can browse but can't read your secrets or memory unless you grant it.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="arch-item">
      <div class="arch-icon">
        <svg width="32" height="32" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><rect x="3" y="3" width="7" height="7"/><rect x="14" y="3" width="7" height="7"/><rect x="3" y="14" width="7" height="7"/><rect x="14" y="14" width="7" height="7"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="arch-title-col">
        <h3 class="arch-title">Multitenant Config</h3>
        <a href="#" class="arch-link">Architecture &#8594;</a>
      </div>
      <div class="arch-desc-col">
        <p class="arch-desc">Manage one agent or hundreds from a single config. Each agent gets its own memory, identity, and secrets while sharing a common daemon and storage layer.</p>
        <p class="arch-scenario">Personal coding agent + work research agent on same machine. Separate memory, secrets, personality. One CLI.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

